title: For Sale:  Sharps New Model 1863 Metallic Conversion Carbine/1864/ ID'd to Cavalry Soldier
postcontent: PHOTO LINK: https://imgur.com/a/O3T2T For sale is a Sharps New Model 1863 Metallic Conversion Carbine – Serial #C,16377, 50-70 U. S. Govt. Cal., 22 inch round barrel, blue/casehardened finish, walnut stock.This is an example of a Sharps Model 1863 carbine that was either arsenal or Sharps Rifle Company converted to .50-70 center fire metallic cartridge with the relined 3 groove barrel. The Ordnance Department contracted with Sharps to convert more than 31,000 Civil War carbines from percussion to center fire configuration in 1867. These carbines were issued to the U. S. Cavalry and along with the Model 1865 Spencer Carbines were the primary cavalry carbines until the Model 1873 Springfield Trapdoor carbine replaced them in 1874 to 1875. The carbine has the standard Lawrence folding leaf rear sight graduated to 800 yards and is fitted with a sling bar and ring on the left side of the stock wrist and receiver. The barrel is absent of the standard Sharps markings and the New Model marking is vary faint and mostly missing. The left rear flat is marked with the letter “S”. “Sharps and R. S. Lawrence” patent markings are on the receiver and lock plate. The serial number is located on the upper tang. The script “DFC“/ribbon final inspection mark applied to Sharps conversion carbines is stamped on the center of the left side of the stock. The rifling is good but has pitting. The bore is good. This is still a VERY shootable rifle! The stock has cracks. The pictures show the condition of the rifle clearly. But for a 154 year old rifle that went through the Civil War, I'd say it ain't too bad!This rifle,as some were, was most likely just taken home or bought by the Cavalryman who it was issued to. His name was John Conroy, of White Plains, NY. His service records are attached. I am assuming he reentered the Army post Civil War, but I did not go farther than his Civil War records. This could just be a rifle he acquired later on too, but I think the evidence is to the contrary. But again, buy the rifle not the story! John Conroy entered the service on October 6,1863 in Oswego, NY, for a 3 year term of service. He was 23 years old. He joined Co. I, 24th NY Infantry. He later transferred as a Private to Co. I, 15th NY Cavalry in November 1863. On June 17, 1865, he was transferred to Co. I, 2nd Provisional NY Cavalry. He was mustered out of service August 9, 1865 at the rank of Private. He dies October 29,1894. He most likely saw several skirmishes in the Shenandoah valley, where some extensive fighting took place. The 15th was part of Sheridan's raid and were at Appomattox to see the surrender of Lee's army.  I included records from the Coates & McAulay book that show the next serial number to this one, C,16378, as being with the 22nd NY Cavalry. I know not all the records with every serial number issued survived, but I do know these were issued out in sequence, so it's not a stretch that both ended up in the NY Cavalry. I see these listed for anywhere from $2,000 for a real beat up one with a sewer pipe barrel and cracked stock , to over $5,000 for a really nice example. I am pricing this one to sell. $1,500.00 plus actual shipping or 6% state tax if sold in Vermont. Email me at REDACTED or call Shawn at REDACTED.  ANTIQUE, SO NO FFL (EXCEPT WHERE REQUIRED). I DO REQUIRE A COPY OF YOUR ID. I take USPS money orders, personal checks with plenty of clear time, discreet Paypal gift, or credit cards plus 3% of the total. title: For Sale:  RARE SKS Poly Tech Hunter Carbine
postcontent: This is NOT your standard SKS. This is 1 of less than 1000 made Norinco SKS Poly Tech Hunter. It is in excellent condition and has a beautiful high gloss stock. Information below comes from this SKS website... http://chinesesks.weebly.com/polyt ech-hunter.html. Call or text at any time. REDACTED. Sorry, I had the wrong # listed before. "The Poly Tech Hunter has the most modifications of any Chinese SKS imported into this country. They are rearsenaled from existing rifles. Get the light just right and you can see were they welded over the previous markings inclusions are even seen on some rifles. You can see this shadow under the new Poly Tech SKS Hunter stamping. 945 is the highest serial number seen.   The first mod was to shorten the barrel to 16.5 inches. Cut off the bayonet lug half way between the front sight and the lug. Install a bushing over the barrel between the gas block and the front sight. The bushing covers the second pin hole from the original FSB, Reinstall the front sight with 1 retaining pin. Then cut the shroud around the sight open as to emulate other military rifles.     They welded up the bayonet groove in the stock ferrule and filled the hole for the cleaning rod with a Uncle Mikes detachable sling swivel. These rifles were not imported by Polytech in Atlanta, Georgia. In actuality they were imported and sold before Kengs switched there name to Polytech. All came through Century Arms International and are import stamped under the barrel.   Next they replaced the rear sight with a windage adjustable sight.   This sight is thicker than the original and requires a relief cut in the bolt carrier above the stripper clip groove.   The original mag is carved and riveted into a 5 rounder. The finished product has 6 rivets on the bottom. There is a metal mag well glued into the stock that goes around the magazine. The bolt wings are relieved for a drop free magazine. Pull on the mag release and the mag will fall out with the charging handle closed. Here is a pic of the mag out of the rifle. Look at it closely. A lot of work went into this mag   All are equipped with a stamped trigger group and a ambidextrous safety. The parts of this rifle are not marked with the serial number. Only the receiver has the serial number on it.    The stocks are only found on this rifle. I don't know what the wood is but the finish is a dark brown. Most have a dull tongue oil finish. While some have the glossy shellack the Chinese are known for. The left side of the stock is cut low for a reason. This allows the use of any drill and tap scope mount without the need to inlet the stock. The rear sling mount is on the bottom of the stock and it comes with the Uncle Mikes detachable sling swivel. These rifles did not come with a sling.The stock has a metal but plate and is not cut for a cleaning kit. It is safe bet to say these rifles started a 00001.  Poly Tech Hunter roll call000190002500026000410006300102001520048000493005490059900675006880072300765007650081200910009370094500985....is the highest number I have a photographic record.........Total 946 rifles"
